identificationModule.briefTitle: DAY101 vs. Standard of Care Chemotherapy in Pediatric Patients With Low-Grade Glioma Requiring First-Line Systemic Therapy (LOGGIC/FIREFLY-2)
identificationModule.officialTitle: LOGGIC/FIREFLY-2: A Phase 3, Randomized, International Multicenter Trial of DAY101 Monotherapy Versus Standard of Care Chemotherapy in Patients With Pediatric Low-Grade Glioma Harboring an Activating RAF Alteration Requiring First-Line Systemic Therapy

collaborators.name: SIOPe Brain Tumor Group LOGGIC Consortium

descriptionModule.briefSummary: This is a 2-arm, randomized, open-label, multicenter, global, Phase 3 trial to evaluate the efficacy, safety, and tolerability of tovorafenib monotherapy versus standard of care (SoC) chemotherapy in patients with pediatric low-grade glioma (LGG) harboring an activating rapidly accelerated fibrosarcoma (RAF) alteration requiring front-line systemic therapy.
descriptionModule.detailedDescription:
Approximately 400 treatment-naïve low-grade glioma patients will be randomized 1:1 to either tovorafenib (Arm 1) or an Investigator's choice of SoC chemotherapy (Arm 2).

Arm 1 (tovorafenib): treatment cycles will repeat every 28 days in the absence of disease progression. Patients will continue tovorafenib until any of the following occurs: disease progression based on Response Assessment in Neuro-Oncology (RANO-LGG) criteria, unacceptable toxicity, withdrawal of consent to treatment, or end of study.

Arm 2 (Investigator's Choice of SoC Chemotherapy): patients will receive one of 3 SoC chemotherapy options selected by the treating Investigator: Children's Oncology Group - Vincristine/Carboplatin (COG-V/C) regimen, International Society for Paediatric Oncology - Low-Grade Glioma Vincristine/Carboplatin (SIOPe-LGG-V/C) regimen, or vinblastine (VBL) regimen. The choice of SoC chemotherapy regimen will be selected prior to patient randomization. Treatment will continue until completion of therapy or until any of the following occurs: disease progression based on RANO-LGG criteria, unacceptable toxicity, withdrawal of consent to treatment, or end of study.

Patients who discontinue treatment due to disease progression will have (1) radiographic evidence of progressive disease based on RANO-LGG, as determined by the Investigator and confirmed by the IRC, or (2) clinical progression based on RANO-LGG criteria determined by the Investigator. Investigators are encouraged to discuss cases of clinical progression and early radiographic progression without clinical symptom with the Sponsor Medical Monitor prior to treatment discontinuation or initiation of a different form of treatment for the malignancy. Patients may continue therapy beyond progressive disease

designInfo.interventionModelDescription: Tovorafenib versus standard of care chemotherapy

armGroups.label: Arm #2
armGroups.description:
Investigator's choice of one of the following current standard of care for pediatric patients with low-grade gliomas:

1. Children's Oncology Group - Vincristine/Carboplatin (COG-V/C)
2. International Society for Paediatric Oncology - Low-Grade Glioma Vincristine/Carboplatin (SIOPe-LGG-V/C)
3. Vinblastine (VBL)

interventions.name: Tovorafenib
interventions.description: Oral type II RAF kinase inhibitor

primaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the objective response rate (ORR) assessed per RANO-LGG criteria by Independent Review Committee (IRC) of tovorafenib monotherapy versus standard of care (SoC) chemotherapy
primaryOutcomes.description: ORR, per RANO-LGG criteria, defined as the proportion of patients with overall confirmed response of complete response (CR) or partial response (PR)

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the progression-free survival (PFS) assessed by IRC of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy per RANO-LGG criteria
secondaryOutcomes.description: PFS per RANO-LGG criteria, deﬁned as time from randomization to PD or death from any cause

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the duration of response (DOR) assessed by IRC of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy per RANO-LGG criteria
secondaryOutcomes.description: DOR per RANO-LGG criteria, deﬁned as time from confirmed response to PD or death from any cause for patients with confirmed response

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the overall survival (OS) of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy
secondaryOutcomes.description: OS, defined as time from randomization up to death from any cause

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the safety and tolerability of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy
secondaryOutcomes.description: Type, frequency, and severity of treatment-emergent adverse events

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the safety and tolerability of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy
secondaryOutcomes.description: Measured by incidence of clinically significant laboratory abnormalities

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Evaluate changes in neurological function and adaptive behavior between tovorafenib versus SoC
secondaryOutcomes.description: Change from baseline in the Vineland Adaptive Behavior Composite Scales \[age-adjusted standard scores range between 20 to 140, with a mean of 100 and standard deviation of 15, and lower scores indicate worse functional outcomes\]

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare changes in visual function outcomes of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy in patients with optic pathway glioma (OPG)
secondaryOutcomes.description: Measured by Teller Acuity Cards® or alternative

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the ORR of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy as assessed by IRC per RANO-HGG and Response Assessment in Pediatric Neuro-Oncology (RAPNO-LGG) criteria
secondaryOutcomes.description: ORR, deﬁned as the proportion of patients with overall conﬁrmed response per RANO-HGG, RANO-LGG, or RAPNO-LGG criteria.

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the clinical beneﬁt rate (CBR) of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy as assessed by IRC per RANO-LGG, RANO-HGG and RAPNO-LGG criteria
secondaryOutcomes.description: CBR, deﬁned as the proportion of patients with radiological tumor stabilization or regression per RANO-LGG, RANO-HGG or RAPNO-LGG criteria, as applicable

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare time to response (TTR) of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy as assessed by IRC per RANO-LGG, RANO-HGG and RAPNO-LGG criteria
secondaryOutcomes.description: Measured by the time to ﬁrst response following initiation of therapy in patients with best overall conﬁrmed response per RANO-LGG, RANO-HGG or RAPNO-LGG criteria, as applicable

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the PFS of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy as assessed by IRC per RAPNO-LGG and RANO-HGG criteria
secondaryOutcomes.description: PFS per RANO-HGG or RAPNO-LGG (as applicable), deﬁned as time from randomization to progressive disease (PD) or death from any cause

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Compare the DOR of tovorafenib monotherapy versus SoC chemotherapy as assessed by IRC per RAPNO-LGG and RANO-HGG criteria
secondaryOutcomes.description: DOR, deﬁned as time from conﬁrmed response to PD or death from any cause for patients with confirmed response per RANO or RAPNO criteria, as applicable

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Evaluate the health-related quality of life (HRQoL) in tovorafenib versus SoC chemotherapy using Patient-Reported Outcomes Measurement Information System (PROMIS) test battery
secondaryOutcomes.description: Measured by change from baseline in Total Score at 1, 2, 5 years

eligibilityModule.eligibilityCriteria:
Inclusion Criteria:

* Less than 25 years of age with LGG with known activating RAF alteration
* Histopathologic diagnosis of glioma or glioneuronal tumor
* At least one measurable lesion as defined by RANO criteria
* Meet indication for first-line systemic therapy

Exclusion Criteria:

* Patient has any of the following tumor-histological findings:

  1. Schwannoma
  2. Subependymal giant cell astrocytoma (Tuberous Sclerosis)
  3. Diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma, even if histologically diagnosed as World Health Organization (WHO) Grade I-II
* Patient's tumor has additional pathogenic molecular alterations, including but not limited to a) IDH 1/2 mutation, b) Histone H3 mutation, and c) NF-1 loss of function alteration.
* Known or suspected diagnosis of neurofibromatosis Type 1 or 2 (NF-1/NF-2)
* Prior or ongoing nonsurgical anticancer therapy for this indication (eg, chemotherapy, oral/intravenous targeted therapy) including radiation
